INSERT INTO `articles` VALUES (1,'DFS','dfs','<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In the DFS (depth-first search) algorithm, we search the graph by visiting successive neighbouring vertices. When we visit a new vertex, we first check all the places that can be reached from it before returning to the previous level. Graphs may contain loops, so a single vertex could be visited multiple times. To avoid this, we use a visited array in which we mark the points that have already been visited.\n  </p>\n\n  <p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In pseudocode, the DFS algorithm can be written as follows:\n  </p>\n\n  <pre class=\"article-paragraph pseudocode\">visited = new Set()\n\nprocedure DFS(node):\n    visited.add(node)\n    for each neighbour in neighbours(node):\n        if neighbour not in visited:\n            DFS(neighbour)</pre>\n\n  <p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    And in the visualisation, the above code will be executed as follows\n  </p>\n \n  <Carousel className=\"max-w-xl\" loop={true}>\n	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 0,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase0.jpg\",\n        description: \"Imagine you are an explorer in a cave system - instead of checking every room near the entrance first, you pick one tunnel and follow it as far as it goes until you hit a wall, only then turning back to find the next path. That\'s how DFS works.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 1,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase1.jpg\",\n        description: \"We begin our journey at Node 1. We mark it as visited. Standing here, we see two possible paths: one leading to Node 2 and another to Node 3. We choose the left branch leading to Node 2.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 2,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase2.jpg\",\n        description: \"We move to Node 2 and mark it as visited. From here, we have two unexplored options: Node 4 and Node 5. We decide to continue our descent further down towards Node 4.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 3,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase3.jpg\",\n        description: \"We reach Node 4 and mark it as visited. Looking around, we find no further unvisited neighbors. We have hit a dead end, so we backtrack to the last node with unexplored options: Node 2.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 4,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase4.jpg\",\n        description: \"Back at Node 2, we take the path we ignored before and move to Node 5. After marking it as visited, we see new tunnels leading to Node 3 and Node 6. We choose to visit Node 3 first.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 5,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase5.jpg\",\n        description: \"We arrive at Node 3 and mark it as visited. This node has a connection leading back to Node 1. However, we must check our \'visited\' array before moving.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 6,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase6.jpg\",\n        description: \"Standing at Node 3, we look at the edge leading to Node 1. Since Node 1 is already marked as visited, we do not follow this path. Having no other unvisited neighbors here, we backtrack to Node 5.\"\n    	}} />\n    	<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 7,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dfs-phases/phase7.jpg\",\n        description: \"Finally, from Node 5, we take the last remaining path to Node 6. We mark it as visited. Now that every reachable node has been explored, our traversal is complete.\"\n    	}} />\n  </Carousel>\n\n  <div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    The above code represents a recursive approach. The computational complexity\n    is then as follows:\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Time complexity: O(V + E)</b>, where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges in the graph.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Space complexity: O(2V) = O(V)</b>, because an additional set/array of visited elements of size V and a stack for recursive calls to the DFS function are required. In the worst case, if the graph is a straight line or a long path, DFS recursion can go as deep as the number of vertices.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    To change the recursive approach to an iterative one, we need to use a stack data structure. The code then looks as follows:\n  </div>\n\n  <pre class=\"article-paragraph pseudocode\">procedure DFS(initialNode):\n    stack = new Array()\n    visited = new Set()\n\n    stack.push(initialNode)\n    visited.add(initialNode)\n\n    while stack is not empty:\n        node = stack.pop()\n\n        for each neighbour in neighbours(node):\n            if neighbour not in visited:\n                stack.push(neighbour)\n                visited.add(neighbour)</pre>\n\n  <div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Time complexity: O(V + E)</b>, where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges in the graph.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Space complexity: O(2V) = O(V)</b>, because an additional set/array of visited elements of size V is required, as well as a stack that will store a total of V vertices.\n  </div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n  <blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n  <b>Optimization Tip: Array vs. Set</b><br />\n  While a <code>Set</code> is conceptually intuitive for tracking visited nodes, using a <b>boolean array</b> of size V is significantly more performant.  Array lookups offer true <b>O(1)</b> performance by leveraging direct memory addressing, effectively bypassing the hashing overhead and collision resolution logic inherent in a <code>Set</code>.\n  </blockquote>\n</div>','[{\"answers\": [\"Depth First Search\", \"Direct Flow System\", \"Data Flow Search\", \"Depth Flow Sequence\"], \"question\": \"What does DFS mean in graph theory?\", \"explanation\": \"DFS stands for Depth First Search – an algorithm for searching a graph in depth.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}, {\"answers\": [\"Queue\", \"Stack\", \"Heap\", \"Priority Queue\"], \"question\": \"What data structure is used to implement DFS iteratively?\", \"explanation\": \"DFS uses a stack in its iterative implementation to track the next vertices to visit.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"O(V)\", \"O(E)\", \"O(V + E)\", \"O(V * E)\"], \"question\": \"What is the time complexity of DFS for a graph with V vertices and E edges?\", \"explanation\": \"DFS visits each vertex and each edge exactly once, resulting in a time complexity of O(V + E).\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"To store vertex values\", \"To avoid visiting the same vertex multiple times\", \"To speed up the algorithm\", \"To store the shortest path\"], \"question\": \"Why is a \'visited\' array needed in DFS?\", \"explanation\": \"A \'visited\' array prevents the algorithm from visiting the same vertices multiple times, which protects against infinite loops in graphs with cycles.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"Post-order\", \"Pre-order\", \"In-order\", \"Level-order\"], \"question\": \"Which tree traversal method corresponds to DFS if it marks a vertex as visited first and then moves to the remaining vertices?\", \"explanation\": \"It is similar to pre-order traversal, where we first visit the starting vertex and go as deep as possible before moving to the other branches.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}]'),(2,'BFS','bfs','<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In the BFS (breadth-first search) algorithm, we explore the graph layer by layer. Instead of going as deep as possible along one path, we first visit all the immediate neighbors of the starting point, then the neighbors of those neighbors, and so on. This is similar to how ripples spread across the surface of a pond when you toss in a stone. To prevent infinite loops and redundant work, we use a visited set to keep track of the nodes we have already encountered.\n</p>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In pseudocode, the BFS algorithm utilizes a queue data structure (FIFO – First In, First Out) and can be written as follows:\n</p>\n\n<pre class=\"article-paragraph pseudocode\">procedure BFS(initialNode):\n    visited = new Set()\n    queue = new Queue()\n\n    visited.add(initialNode)\n    queue.enqueue(initialNode)\n\n    while queue is not empty:\n        node = queue.dequeue()\n        \n        for each neighbour in neighbours(node):\n            if neighbour not in visited:\n                visited.add(neighbour)\n                queue.enqueue(neighbour)\n</pre>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In the visualization, the code above will be executed as follows:\n</p>\n\n<Carousel className=\"max-w-xl\" loop={true}>\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 0,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase0.jpg\",\n        description: \"Imagine you are searching for someone in a building - instead of running down one hallway to the very end, you check every room on the first floor before moving up to the second. That is how BFS explores level by level.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 1,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase1.jpg\",\n        description: \"We start our journey at Node 1. We mark it as visited and place it in our queue. This is the starting point from which we will discover all nearby nodes.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 2,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase2.jpg\",\n        description: \"We remove Node 1 from the queue and look at its neighbors. The first one we find is Node 2. We mark it as visited and add it to the queue. It is now part of our Layer 1.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 3,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase3.jpg\",\n        description: \"Still checking neighbors of Node 1, we discover Node 3. We mark it as visited and add it to the queue. Node 1 is now fully processed, and our queue currently holds [Node 2, Node 3].\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 4,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase4.jpg\",\n        description: \"Next, we take Node 2 out of the queue. Among its neighbors, we find Node 4. Since it\'s unvisited, we mark it and add it to the back of the queue. We are now moving into the Layer 2.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 5,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase5.jpg\",\n        description: \"Now we process Node 3 from the queue. We find its neighbor, Node 5. We mark Node 5 as visited and add it to the queue. We have now discovered all nodes that are two steps away from the start. After marking Node 5, we take Node 4 from the queue. We check its connections, but since it has no unvisited neighbors, it is simply removed without adding new nodes.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 6,\n        url: \"/images/graph/bfs-phases/phase6.jpg\",\n        description: \"Finally, we reach the last unvisited node. From Node 5, we discover Node 6. We mark it as visited and add it to the queue. Once the queue is emptied of the remaining nodes, the BFS traversal is complete!\"\n    }} />\n</Carousel>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    The BFS algorithm is inherently iterative. Its computational complexity is as follows:\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Time complexity: O(V + E)</b>, where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges. Every vertex is enqueued exactly once, and every edge is checked once when looking at neighbors.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Space complexity: O(V)</b>, because in the worst case the queue and the visited set stores all vertices.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n        <b>Implementation Tip: Array vs. Set</b><br />\n        While using a <code>Set</code> is more flexible (especially if your nodes are named with strings or large, non-sequential numbers), using a <b>boolean array</b> is significantly faster in most competitive programming and production scenarios because arrays offer true O(1) access via memory offsets. \n    </blockquote>\n</div>','[{\"answers\": [\"Breadth First Search\", \"Binary Finder System\", \"Basic Flow Search\", \"Breadth Functional Search\"], \"question\": \"What does BFS stand for in graph theory?\", \"explanation\": \"BFS stands for Breadth First Search - an algorithm that explores the graph layer by layer, starting from the root or an initial node.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}, {\"answers\": [\"Stack\", \"Array\", \"Queue\", \"Linked List\"], \"question\": \"Which data structure is used to manage the order of visited nodes in BFS?\", \"explanation\": \"BFS uses a Queue (FIFO - First In, First Out) to ensure that nodes are visited in the order they were discovered, layer by layer.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"Exploring a tunnel until a dead end\", \"Ripples spreading on a pond\", \"Climbing a ladder\", \"Reading a book page by page\"], \"question\": \"Which metaphor was used in the text to describe how BFS works?\", \"explanation\": \"The text compares BFS to ripples spreading on a pond because it moves outward from the starting point to all immediate neighbors before going further.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"O(V)\", \"O(E)\", \"O(V + E)\", \"O(1)\"], \"question\": \"What is the time complexity of BFS for a graph with V vertices and E edges?\", \"explanation\": \"BFS has a time complexity of O(V + E) because it visits each vertex and checks each edge exactly once.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"It is more flexible\", \"It handles string-named nodes better\", \"It offers true O(1) access via memory offsets\", \"It uses less total memory than an array\"], \"question\": \"According to the implementation tip, why is a boolean array faster than a Set for tracking visited nodes?\", \"explanation\": \"A boolean array is faster because it provides true O(1) access through direct memory offsets, while a Set relies on hashing which has more overhead.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"O(log V)\", \"O(V)\", \"O(V + E)\", \"O(E)\"], \"question\": \"What is the worst-case space complexity for BFS?\", \"explanation\": \"The space complexity is O(V) because, in the worst case (like a star graph), the queue or the visited array might need to store nearly all vertices at once.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"Backtracking\", \"Level-order traversal\", \"Going as deep as possible\", \"Recursive calls only\"], \"question\": \"What is the primary characteristic of a BFS traversal?\", \"explanation\": \"The primary characteristic of BFS is level-order traversal, meaning it visits all nodes at the current distance (layer) before moving to the next distance.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}]'),(3,'Dijkstra Algorithm - Shortest Path','dijkstra','<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\nDijkstra\'s Algorithm is the gold standard for finding the <b>shortest path</b> between nodes in a weighted graph. While BFS handles unweighted graphs layer by layer, Dijkstra accounts for the cost (weight) of each edge. Imagine you are using a GPS: instead of just taking the road with the fewest turns, you want the one that takes the least amount of time. To achieve this, the algorithm always picks the cheapest unexplored node next, ensuring that once a node is processed, we have found the absolute shortest way to reach it.\n</p>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Note:</b> Dijkstra assumes that adding an edge always increases (or keeps constant) the total path distance. If your graph contains <b>negative weights</b>, this greedy assumption breaks, and you should reach for the <i>Bellman-Ford</i> algorithm instead.\n</p>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In pseudocode, Dijkstra\'s algorithm utilizes a <b>Priority Queue</b> (Min-Heap) to always select the node with the smallest current distance.\n</p>\n\n<pre class=\"article-paragraph pseudocode\">{`procedure Dijkstra(Graph, startNode):\n\n    # Initialize distances as infinite and previous nodes as undefined\n    distance = new Array(Graph.count_vertices)\n    previous = new Array(Graph.count_vertices)\n\n    for each vertex v in Graph:\n        distance[v] = Infinity\n        previous[v] = undefined\n\n    # Distance to the source is always zero\n    distance[startNode] = 0\n\n    # Initialize priority queue with the start node\n    priorityQueue = new MinPriorityQueue() # sort by distance - item[1]\n    priorityQueue.insert([startNode, 0])\n\n    while priorityQueue is not empty:\n\n        # Extract the node with the smallest known distance\n        [node, dist] = priorityQueue.extractMin()\n\n        # Skip if a shorter path to this node was already processed\n        if dist > distance[node]:\n            continue\n\n        # Check each neighbor of the current node\n        for each neighbour in neighbours(node):\n\n            # Calculate the total distance to the neighbor through this node\n            newDistance = distance[node] + weight(node, neighbour)\n\n            # If a shorter path to the neighbor is found\n            if newDistance < distance[neighbour]:\n\n                # Update the best distance and record the path\n                distance[neighbour] = newDistance\n                previous[neighbour] = node\n\n                # Add the improved path to the queue\n                priorityQueue.insert([neighbour, newDistance])`}</pre>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\nThe <b>distance</b> array is essential because it acts as the memory of the shortest path found so far for every single node in your graph. The <b>previous</b> array is necessary because the distance array only stores the cost of the trip, not the actual turns you took to get there. Every time you find a new shortest distance to a neighbor, you update the previous pointer to point back to the current node. This allows you to reconstruct the entire route at the very end by backtracking from the destination to the start, step by step.\n</p>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    In the visualization, the algorithm processes the graph by constantly relaxing edges to find shorter routes:\n</p>\n\n<Carousel className=\"max-w-xl\" loop={true}>\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 0,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase0.jpg\",\n        description: \"We initialize the graph: all distances in our dist array are set to infinity, except for Node 1, which starts at 0 as our point of origin.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 1,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase1.jpg\",\n        description: \"Node 1 is processed and settled (turns blue). We now examine its outgoing edges to see which neighbors we can discover for the first time.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 2,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase2.jpg\",\n        description: \"Discovery phase: We find Node 3 (weight 3) and Node 2 (weight 6). Both are added to our queue as potential candidates for the next step.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 3,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase3.jpg\",\n        description: \"The algorithm greedily picks the cheapest option. Since Node 3 (dist 3) is closer than Node 2 (dist 6), it is settled and turns blue.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 4,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase4.jpg\",\n        description: \"From Node 3, we explore further and find Node 5. The total cost to reach it through this path is 11 (3 + 8), which we record in our queue.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 5,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase5.jpg\",\n        description: \"Returning to our queue, the cheapest available path now leads to Node 2. We settle it and prepare to examine its outgoing connections.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 6,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase6.jpg\",\n        description: \"Relaxation occurs! Through Node 2, we find Node 4 (6 + 1 = 7). More importantly, we find a new path to Node 5 (6 + 2 = 8), which is cheaper than our previous 11. We update Node 5 with this better value.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 7,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase7.jpg\",\n        description: \"Following the priority queue, the next cheapest node is Node 4 (dist 7). We mark it as settled and check for any further paths (finding none).\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 8,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase8.jpg\",\n        description: \"We now pull the next best option from the queue: Node 5 (dist 8). We mark it as settled and look for its unexplored neighbors.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 9,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase9.jpg\",\n        description: \"From Node 5, we discover the final node. The total cost to reach Node 6 through our optimized path is 13 (8 + 5). We add this to the queue.\"\n    }} />\n    <CarouselSlide slide={{\n        id: 10,\n        url: \"/images/graph/dijkstra-phases/phase10.jpg\",\n        description: \"Mission accomplished! All nodes have turned blue. We have successfully determined the absolute shortest paths from Node 1 to every other node in the graph.\"\n    }} />\n</Carousel>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Time complexity: O((V + E) lg V)</b>, when using a binary heap. We perform V extracts of the minimum element and up to E updates to the distances (relaxations).\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <b>Space complexity: O(V)</b>, as we need to store the shortest distance to every vertex and maintain the priority queue.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n        <b>Implementation Tip: Priority Queue vs. Simple Array</b><br />\n        If you use a simple array to find the minimum distance, your time complexity becomes O(V^2). For most cases, a <b>Binary Heap</b> is the standard. However, for the absolute theoretical speed limit, using a <b>Fibonacci Heap</b> reduces the complexity to O(E + V lg V).\n    </blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n    <blockquote class=\"article-blockquote-warning\">\n        <b>Critical Constraint: No Negative Edges</b><br />\n        Dijkstra\'s algorithm will <b>not work</b> correctly if there are negative edge weights. Because it\'s a greedy algorithm, once it marks a node as settled (blue), it never visits it again. A negative edge could potentially offer a shorter path to an already settled node, which Dijkstra would completely miss.\n    </blockquote>\n</div>\n','[{\"answers\": [\"Finding any path in a graph\", \"Finding the shortest path in a non-negative weighted graph\", \"Detecting cycles in a directed graph\", \"Finding the longest path in a graph\"], \"question\": \"What is the primary purpose of Dijkstra\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"Dijkstra\'s algorithm is specifically designed to find the shortest path between a source node and all other reachable nodes in a non-negative weighted graph.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"Stack (LIFO)\", \"Simple Queue (FIFO)\", \"Priority Queue (Min-Heap)\", \"Linked List\"], \"question\": \"Which data structure is essential for an efficient implementation of Dijkstra\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"A Priority Queue (Min-Heap) allows the algorithm to quickly extract the node with the smallest current distance, which is key to its performance.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"Removing edges with heavy weights\", \"A technique to speed up the algorithm\'s runtime\", \"The process of updating a node\'s distance if a shorter path is found\", \"Resetting all distances back to infinity\"], \"question\": \"What does \\\"edge relaxation\\\" refer to in Dijkstra\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"Relaxation is the core step where the algorithm checks if the path to a neighbor through the current node is shorter than the previously known distance.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"Because the path through Node 2 (dist 8) was shorter than through Node 3 (dist 11)\", \"Because Node 3 was removed from the graph\", \"Because Node 5 was found to be a dead end\", \"Because Node 2 had more neighbors than Node 3\"], \"question\": \"In the provided visualization, why was Node 5\'s distance updated from 11 to 8?\", \"explanation\": \"This is a classic relaxation: the algorithm found a shorter route (1 -> 2 -> 5) costing 8, which is better than the original route (1 -> 3 -> 5) costing 11.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}, {\"answers\": [\"O(V + E)\", \"O(V^2)\", \"O((V + E) log V)\", \"O(E + V)\"], \"question\": \"What is the time complexity of Dijkstra\'s algorithm using a binary priority queue?\", \"explanation\": \"With a binary heap, the complexity is O((V + E) log V) due to the V extract-min operations and E edge relaxation operations.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"When it is first added to the priority queue\", \"When it is popped from the priority queue\", \"When all of its neighbors have been discovered\", \"When the algorithm completes its very first step\"], \"question\": \"At what point is a node considered settled (blue) in Dijkstra\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"A node is settled only when it is popped from the priority queue. At this point, the shortest path to it is guaranteed to have been found.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"BFS visits nodes layer by layer. Dijkstra accounts for edge weights\", \"BFS uses a stack. Dijkstra uses a queue\", \"BFS only works on directed graphs\", \"There is no difference between them\"], \"question\": \"What is the main difference between BFS and Dijkstra\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"BFS treats all edges as having a cost of 1 (unweighted), while Dijkstra evaluates the actual numerical weights on each edge to find the shortest path.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}]'),(4,'Eulerian Path/Cycle','eulerian-path-cycle','<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\nAn <b>Eulerian Cycle</b> is a classic graph theory problem that traces back to the famous Seven Bridges of Königsberg. While Dijkstra’s focuses on the <i>cheapest</i> path, Euler asks: \"Can I traverse <b>every single edge</b> exactly once and return to the start?\" It is the digital equivalent of drawing a complex shape without ever lifting your pen from the paper. If you manage to visit every edge but end at a different node than where you started, you have found an <b>Eulerian Path</b>.\n</p>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n<b>Selecting the Starting Vertex: Undirected Graphs</b><br />\nIn an undirected graph, starting from the correct vertex is crucial for the algorithm to succeed:\n<ul>\n<li><b>Eulerian Circuit:</b> If all vertices have an <b>even degree</b>, the algorithm can start from <b>any vertex</b>.</li>\n<li><b>Eulerian Path:</b> If there are exactly <b>two vertices with an odd degree</b>, the algorithm must start from <b>one of those two vertices</b>.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n<b>Selecting the Starting Vertex: Directed Graphs</b><br />\nFor directed graphs, the conditions depend on the balance of in-degrees and out-degrees:\n<ul>\n<li><b>Eulerian Circuit:</b> If all vertices have an <b>equal number</b> of incoming and outgoing edges, you can start from <b>any vertex</b>.</li>\n<li><b>Eulerian Path:</b> If exactly one vertex has <b>one more outgoing edge</b> than incoming (the start) and exactly one vertex has <b>one more incoming edge</b> than outgoing (the end), you must start at the vertex with the extra outgoing edge.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\nTo find the path, we use a recursive approach that explores the graph and creates the route during the backtracking phase.\n</p>\n\n<pre class=\"article-paragraph pseudocode\">{`procedure FindEulerPath(Graph, startNode):\n    path = new Array()\n\n    procedure EulerPath(V):\n        for each edge (V, U) in Graph:\n            remove edge (V, U)\n            if Graph is undirected:\n                remove edge (U, V)\n            EulerPath(U)\n        path.push(V)\n\n    EulerPath(startNode)\n\n    return path.reverse()`}\n</pre>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\nIn the visualization, the algorithm removes edges and builds the final route while backtracking. Note that because we add the vertex to the path after the recursion, the resulting array will be the <b>reverse</b> of the actual travel order.\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<Carousel className=\"max-w-xl\" loop={true}>\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 0,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase0.jpg\",\ndescription: \"Think of an Eulerian Path like drawing a shape without lifting your pen. If you return to your start, it\'s a Cycle. If you hit a dead end, it\'s a Path. Retracing a line is strictly forbidden!\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 1,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase1.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We move from Node 1 to Node 3. Edge (1, 3) is removed and turns blue. Node 3 becomes our active vertex.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 2,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase2.jpg\",\ndescription: \"The recursion dives deeper. We traverse to Node 4, removing edge (3, 4).\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 3,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase3.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We move from Node 4 to Node 6. Edge (4, 6) turns blue as it is deleted from the available graph.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 4,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase4.jpg\",\ndescription: \"From Node 6, we travel to Node 2. Edge (6, 2) is removed. Every step forward adds a new layer to our recursion stack.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 5,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase5.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We move from Node 2 back to Node 3. Edge (2, 3) is removed. The algorithm is currently tracing a sub-cycle within the graph.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 6,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase6.jpg\",\ndescription: \"From Node 3, the only available path is toward Node 5. Edge (3, 5) turns blue.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 7,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase7.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We move from Node 5 to Node 6. Edge (5, 6) is removed. We are rapidly running out of edges to traverse.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 8,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase8.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We move from Node 6 to Node 4. Edge (6, 4) turns blue. The graph is now empty of available edges.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 9,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase9.jpg\",\ndescription: \"Dead End reached! Node 4 has no edges left. The recursion bottoms out and adds Node 4 to the path.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 10,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase10.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We return to Node 6. Since its edges are already gone, it is finalized and added to the path array.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 11,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase11.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We backtrack to Node 5. It is added to our path. Remember: because we add nodes while backtracking, the destination appears first!\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 12,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase12.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We return to Node 3. All its neighbors have been visited, so it is finalized and turns blue with a white border.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 13,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase13.jpg\",\ndescription: \"The recursive call for Node 2 is now finishing. Since all its connected edges are already blue (removed), Node 2 is added to the path.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 14,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase14.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We return to Node 6. Note that we passed through here earlier, but only now - after all its sub-branches are explored - does it get finalized and added to our path.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 15,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase15.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We backtrack to Node 4. The function call that took us from 4 to 6 is officially over. Node 4 turns blue with a white border.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 16,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase16.jpg\",\ndescription: \"We return to Node 3. Every single edge leading out of this node has been processed. It is added to the path array, leaving only our starting point to be finalized.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 17,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase17.jpg\",\ndescription: \"Finally, we return to Node 1. Since all edges in the entire graph are gone, our starting node turns blue with a white border.\"\n}} />\n<CarouselSlide slide={{\nid: 18,\nurl: \"/images/graph/euler-phases/phase18.jpg\",\ndescription: \"Mission accomplished! We take our back-to-front array and reverse it. The result is a perfect Eulerian Path: 1->3->4->6->2->3->5->6->4.\"\n}} />\n</Carousel>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<b>Time complexity: O(V + E)</b>. We visit every edge exactly once and perform constant-time deletions and additions.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<b>Space complexity: O(V + E)</b>, primarily due to the recursion stack and the storage of the resulting path.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote-warning\">\n<b>Critical Constraint: Connectivity is Key</b><br />\nEven if your degrees are perfect, the algorithm fails if the graph is <b>disconnected</b>. All edges must belong to a single connected component (ignoring isolated vertices with no edges) for an Eulerian Path to exist.\n</blockquote>\n</div>','[{\"answers\": [\"Every vertex must have an even degree\", \"Exactly two vertices must have an odd degree\", \"At least one vertex must have an odd degree\", \"All vertices must be connected to a central hub\"], \"question\": \"In an undirected graph, what is the mandatory condition for an Eulerian Cycle to exist?\", \"explanation\": \"An Eulerian Cycle requires every vertex to have an even degree so that every entry into a vertex has a corresponding exit.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}, {\"answers\": [\"0\", \"1\", \"2\", \"3\"], \"question\": \"How many vertices of odd degree are allowed in an undirected graph that contains an Eulerian Path but NO cycle?\", \"explanation\": \"An Eulerian Path exists if exactly two vertices have an odd degree; these serve as the start and end points.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"In-degree equals out-degree for all vertices\", \"One vertex has in-degree = out-degree + 1, and another has out-degree = in-degree + 1\", \"All vertices have more outgoing than incoming edges\", \"The graph must be a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)\"], \"question\": \"What is the condition for an Eulerian Cycle in a directed graph?\", \"explanation\": \"In a directed graph, a cycle exists only if every single vertex has an in-degree equal to its out-degree.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}, {\"answers\": [\"The edges are removed as they are traversed\", \"The vertices are sorted alphabetically\", \"It uses a Priority Queue to find the smallest edge\", \"It only works on graphs with negative weights\"], \"question\": \"How does the provided pseudocode find the Eulerian route during the DFS?\", \"explanation\": \"The algorithm removes edges once they are used and adds the vertex to the path during the backtracking phase to ensure all sub-circuits are covered.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"The resulting path is in correct order\", \"The resulting path is the reverse of the travel order\", \"The path only contains the start and end nodes\", \"The path is sorted by vertex degree\"], \"question\": \"Because nodes are added to the path array during the backtracking phase (after the recursive call), what must be done to the array at the end?\", \"explanation\": \"Since nodes are added as the recursion \'unwinds,\' the final array is the reverse of the actual traversal and must be reversed.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}]'),(5,'Kosaraju Algorithm - Strongly Connected Components','kosaraju-scc','<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<b>Kosaraju’s Algorithm</b> is a powerful technique designed to find <b>Strongly Connected Components (SCCs)</b> in a directed graph. In a directed graph, an SCC is a maximal subgraph where every vertex is reachable from every other vertex. If you can travel from node A to node B and also back from B to A, they belong to the same SCC.\n</p>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n<b>The Core Intuition: The Transpose Trick</b><br />\nThe genius of Kosaraju’s lies in the <b>Reverse (Transpose) Graph</b>. If you can travel from node A to node B in the original graph, and you can still travel from A to B after reversing every single arrow, then A and B must be part of the same tightly knit component.\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"article-paragraph\">\nTo isolate these components, the algorithm uses two separate Depth First Search (DFS) passes. The first pass determines a specific finishing order that ensures we process components in the correct sequence during the second pass.\n</p>\n\n<pre class=\"article-paragraph pseudocode\">{`procedure Kosaraju(G):\n    S = new Array()\n    visited = new Set()\n\n    # Step 1: DFS on original graph to fill stack\n    for each node in G:\n        if node not in visited:\n            DFS1(node)\n\n    # Step 2: Transpose the graph\n    GT = transpose(G)\n\n    # Step 3: DFS on transposed graph in stack order\n    visited = new Set()\n    SCCs = new Array()\n\n    while S not empty:\n        node = S.pop()\n        if node not in visited:\n            component = new Array()\n            DFS2(node, component)\n            SCCs.push(component)\n\n    return SCCs\n\nprocedure DFS1(node):\n    visited.add(node)\n    for each neighbour in neighbours(node, in G):\n        if neighbour not in visited:\n            DFS1(neighbour)\n    S.push(node)\n\nprocedure DFS2(node, component):\n    visited.add(node)\n    component.push(node)\n    for each neighbour in neighbours(node, in GT):\n        if neighbour not in visited:\n            DFS2(neighbour, component)\n\nprocedure transpose(G):\n    GT = new Graph()\n    for each (u, v) in G.edges:\n        add edge (v, u) to GT\n    return GT`}\n</pre>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n<b>Why the Stack?</b><br />\nBy popping nodes from the stack (last finished, first out), we effectively process the graph from sink to source. Because the graph is reversed in the second pass, these sinks become sources, which prevents our DFS from leaking out of one SCC into another.\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<Carousel className=\"max-w-xl\" loop={true}>\n  <CarouselSlide slide={{\n    id: 0,\n    url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase0.jpg\",\n    description: \"We start with all nodes in white, meaning they are completely untouched. Our goal is to find which ones belong together in a cycle.\"\n  }} />\n  \n<CarouselSlide slide={{\n  id: 1,\n  url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase1.jpg\",\n  description: \"The mission is underway! Nodes 1, 3, 5, and 6 have turned blue as we scout them out. Since Node 6 leads nowhere else, we\'ve reached our first dead end - this means it\'s time to add it to our order array as the first node to finish its journey.\"\n}} />\n  \n  <CarouselSlide slide={{\n    id: 2,\n    url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase2.jpg\",\n    description: \"Almost there! Most of the graph is blue, but Node 4 is still white because we haven\'t reached it yet. We\'re still finishing up the first pass through the other branches. The gray edge show where we checked for a path but found a node we already visited.\"\n  }} />\n  \n <CarouselSlide slide={{\n  id: 3,\n  url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase3.jpg\",\n  description: \"Upon reaching Node 4, we hit our next dead end. Since there are no more white nodes left to explore, Node 4 is added to the list. As the search backtracks through the remaining nodes, everyone finally gets their order, resulting in the completed order: [6, 4, 2, 5, 3, 1].\"\n}} />\n  \n  <CarouselSlide slide={{\n    id: 4,\n    url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase4.jpg\",\n    description: \"Now we flip every single arrow. Reversing the graph is a clever way to see if a node can actually reach back to its starting point. We reset the colors back to white to start our second pass. We\'ll now pull nodes from our order array, starting from the very last one we finished (order array: [6, 4, 2, 5, 3, 1]).\"\n  }} />\n  \n  <CarouselSlide slide={{\n    id: 5,\n    url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase5.jpg\",\n    description: \"We pick a node 1 and see who it can reach through the reversed arrows. Nodes 1, 2, 3, and 5 turn blue together. They are officially a Secret Society because they are all reachable from each other in both directions. Nodes 2, 5, and 3 are already in a Secret Society, so we skip them. Only 4 and 6 remain on our order array! (order array: [6, 4]).\"\n  }} />\n  \n  <CarouselSlide slide={{\n    id: 6,\n    url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase6.jpg\",\n    description: \"Next, we find a component consisting only of Node 4. It stands alone as its own solitary Secret Society.\"\n  }} />\n  \n  <CarouselSlide slide={{\n    id: 7,\n    url: \"/images/graph/kosaraju-phases/phase7.jpg\",\n    description: \"At the end, we find a component consisting only of Node 6. It stands alone as its own solitary Secret Society. Our final Secret Societies are: [3, 5, 2, 1], [4] and [6].\"\n  }} />\n</Carousel>\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<b>Time complexity: O(V + E)</b>. The algorithm performs two linear-time traversals and one graph reversal, making it highly efficient for large datasets.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<b>Space complexity: O(V + E)</b>. This is required to store the reversed version of the graph, the visited set, and the recursion stack.\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote-warning\">\n<b>Single Nodes as SCCs</b><br />\nA vertex that is not part of any cycle is still considered a Strongly Connected Component of size one. Every vertex in a directed graph belongs to exactly one SCC.\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"article-paragraph\">\n<blockquote class=\"article-blockquote\">\n<b>Alternative Approach: Tarjan’s Algorithm</b><br />\nWhile Kosaraju’s is often praised for its conceptual simplicity, <b>Tarjan’s Algorithm</b> is a powerful alternative that finds all SCCs in a single DFS pass. Because it tracks discovery times and low-link values, Tarjan’s is highly flexible - with minor modifications, the same logic can be used to identify <b>bridges</b> and <b>articulation points</b> in <b>undirected graph</b>.\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n','[{\"answers\": [\"Any node can reach any other node in the group\", \"There are no cycles in the group\", \"The group has only one incoming edge\", \"The group contains the shortest path of the graph\"], \"question\": \"What defines a Strongly Connected Component (SCC) in a directed graph?\", \"explanation\": \"An SCC is a maximal subgraph where every vertex is reachable from every other vertex within that same subgraph.\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}, {\"answers\": [\"To find the shortest paths\", \"To identify leaf nodes\", \"To determine the order of processing for the second pass\", \"To remove cycles from the graph\"], \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the first DFS pass and the stack in Kosaraju\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"The first pass records the finishing times of nodes. Processing them in this order in the second pass ensures we visit SCCs correctly without leaking into other components.\", \"correctAnswer\": 3}, {\"answers\": [\"It makes the graph undirected\", \"It reverses the direction of all edges\", \"It doubles the number of edges\", \"It removes all self-loops\"], \"question\": \"What happens during the transpose step of Kosaraju\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"Transposing a graph means reversing the direction of every directed edge (if u -> v existed, it becomes v -> u).\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"In the original edge direction\", \"In the reversed (transpose) edge direction\", \"By following the highest degree nodes\", \"By skipping the stack order\"], \"question\": \"In the third step of the algorithm, how is the second DFS performed?\", \"explanation\": \"The second DFS is performed on the transposed graph, starting from unvisited nodes in the order they appear on the stack.\", \"correctAnswer\": 2}, {\"answers\": [\"O(V + E)\", \"O(V^2)\", \"O(log V)\", \"O(E^2)\"], \"question\": \"What is the time complexity of Kosaraju\'s algorithm?\", \"explanation\": \"Since it involves two DFS traversals and one graph transposition, the total time complexity is linear, O(V + E).\", \"correctAnswer\": 1}]');
